[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Joab the son of Zeruiah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Zeruiah was David’s sister (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 2:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and Joab the most prominent of her three distinguished sons. Subsequently, by his successful leading of the forlorn hope in the siege of Jerusalem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Chronicles 11:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 5:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), he became permanently established as commanaer-in-chief of David’s army. He was undoubtedly among “the brethren of David” who came down to him at the cave of Adullam (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 22:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), though he is not mentioned by name, like his brother Abishai (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 26:6-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in the narrative of David’s outlawry.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The pool of Gibeon is a large reservoir or tank, arranged to store the overflow from a subterranean reservoir fed by a spring in the rocky hill-side. Its ruins still remain, about 120 feet long by 100 broad. The hostile forces halted in full sight of each other on the opposite sides of the pool.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The pool of Gibeon",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is a large reservoir or tank, arranged to store the overflow from a subterranean reservoir fed by a spring in the rocky hill-side. Its ruins still remain, about 120 feet long by 100 broad. The hostile forces halted in full sight of each other on the opposite sides of the pool.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
